General accidental release prevention and chemical-specific prevention steps:

MPM Silicones has implemented a comprehensive program to prevent accidental releases of hazardous chemicals known as Process Safety Management (PSM).  The facility is also subject to the New York State Chemical Bulk Storage (CBS) regulation that focuses on preventing spills and releases from hazardous material storage tanks.  Both programs are an integral part of the safety-related operations at MPM Silicones, LLC.  PSM helps to ensure that proper safety information is in place, operating procedures are followed, chemical hazards are identified, employees and contractors are properly trained, and critical equipment is properly inspected and maintained.  Some of the many specific features in place at MPM Silicones, LLC to minimize the potential for a chemical accident include:
* Computerized process control systems on chlorosilane and methyl chloride chemical reaction and purification systems to ensure that any deviations from the intended operating conditions (e.g. pressure, temperature, vessel level, flow rate) are immediately identified and corrected;
* Instrumentation and safety procedures that reduce the potential for human error that could lead to a storage tank overfill;
* Secondary containment dikes around storage tanks and loading stations to contain a spill;
* Hydrogen chloride and methyl chloride gas sensors to detect and warn of a release;
* Extensive safety information about the processes reviewed with employees and contractors;
* Written operating procedures that include emergency response actions and safety shut down instructions;
* Comprehensive employee and contractor training programs to promote consistently safe work practices and proper operation of processes;
* Maintenance and inspection programs t

o ensure ongoing equipment reliability and integrity including equipment testing and inspection;
* A management of change process that requires the review of proposed plant modifications in order to identify possible hazards before the change is implemented;
* Safety pre-qualification of all contractors;
* Safety reviews prior to startup of processes; and
* Safety systems and procedures that control hazards during special operations such as welding.

Due to the size and complexity of the facility, PSM and RMP Program 3 activities occur on a continuous basis. As such all of the information contained in Section 7, with the exception of question 7.5, of this report are accurate as of February 11, 2010.

Five-year accident history:

The MPM Silicones, LLC facility experienced two RMP-related incidents in the past five years.  

In 2007, approximately 1182 lbs of hydrogen chloride and 2139 lbs of MCS crude were released as a result of the failure of two transfer hoses during a transfer procedure. The leading end of each hose failed, releasing liquid MCS crude to adjacent floor. The reaction of MCS crude with moisture in the air caused the release of a hydrogen chloride vapor cloud. All MCS crude liquid was believed to be contained and directed to the process sewer. Adjacent roadway RT 4 & 32 was closed to traffic and Momentive personnel interviews recount the Waterford police attempting to notify individuals in neighboring homes. However, Momentive never received an ensuing police report that documents this effort. In an effort to prevent this type of event in the future the non-conductive hoses involved in this incident were replaced with conductive hoses for this process and in all production areas involved in non-conductive fluid transfers and updates were made to the facility's Safe Work Permit.

